&gt; If anyone is interested, I can send you a copy of the Excel 
spreadsheet that
&gt; Richard mentioned.  While hardly a scientific sample, what I did 
was to go
&gt; through the Tokyo National Museum Uchigatana Koshirae book and 
record the
&gt; tsuba diameter, saya length and tsuka length for each illustrated 
katana or
&gt; wakizashi koshirae.  It&#39;s somewhat interesting to play with.
&gt; 
&gt; It turns out that correlation between saya length (a proxy for 
blade length)
&gt; and tsuba diameter is fairly weak.  The correlation between tsuka 
length and
&gt; tsuba size is actually better.  The correlation between saya length 
and
&gt; tsuka length is very good.
&gt; 
&gt; The average katana tsuba is 8.03 cm in diameter, but the range is 
5.85-10.80
&gt; cm.
&gt; The average wakizashi tsuba is 6.59 cm in diameter, with a range of 
4.90 to
&gt; 8.60 cm.
&gt; 
&gt; So, making definite statements about katana-size or wakizashi-sized 
tsuba on
&gt; size alone is pretty difficult.  There are no dates given for most 
of the
&gt; koshirae in the book, so that is not included in the spreadsheet.  
There&#39;s
&gt; more work to do here.
